title: College Roundup: St. Mary's grad Lewnes named UMBC lacrosse captain
text:
Mids ultimately wore down against Notre Dame (Bill Wagner) 
Wetherby garnered her first career Patriot League Goalkeeper of the Week honor, recording a game-high seven saves in Navy's 0-0 draw with Bucknell. She tallied her third consecutive clean sheet to extend her scoreless streak to 332:55 minutes. All three shutouts have come against league opponents (Lehigh, Holy Cross and Bucknell) and lowered her goals-against average from 1.43 to 1.29. 
NAVY SAILING: Navy sophomore Gary Prieto was off to a hot start to the season in singlehanded sailing, finishing top three in his first two events of the season. When it mattered most this past weekend at the MAISA Men's Singlehanded Championship for the Carl Van Duyne Trophy in Kings Point, N.Y., Prieto came through again, finishing second overall and punching his ticket to the National Championship Nov. 6-8 in Norfolk, Va. 
The Navy varsity offshore sailing team had six teams competing in the Annapolis Yacht Club Fall Series No. 2 Distance Race. In PHRF class A2, senior Nick Woods led his team to first in the 11-boat fleet while senior Tom Wester was second, senior Charlie Morris was fourth and senior Jackson Niketas was fifth. In the J/105 class, junior Phil Campbell finished second of 11 finishers while junior Ethan Doherty was 11th. 
NAVY SQUASH: After winning the Maryland State Open Doubles Squash Championship two weeks ago, the Navy tandem of Bill Kacergis and Senen Ubina secured their second doubles title of the fall by winning the 2015 U.S. Intercollegiate Squash Doubles Championship in Philadelphia over the weekend. 
MARYLAND BASKETBALL: The Terps will host the 2015 Magic Maryland Madness on Saturday, 6 p.m. in XFINITY Center. Maryland Madness will be the first chance for fans to get a glimpse of the 2015-16 Maryland men's and women's basketball teams. Doors will open at 4 p.m. with autographs beginning at 4:30 p.m. Admission to the evening's activities is free (no ticket required) and seating is first-come, first-serve. 
SALISBURY WOMEN'S SOCCER: Senior Samantha Beck notched two first-half goals and an assist to lead the Sea Gulls to a 4-0 victory over Southern Virginia University on Monday afternoon in Capital Athletic Conference play. 
UMBC MEN'S SOCCER: Junior goalkeeper Billy Heavner was tabbed co-America East Men's Soccer Player of the Week. Heavner tied a career high with six saves in the Retrievers' hard-earned 1-0 victory over Albany in Saturday's Homecoming Day contest. 
ST. MARY'S WOMEN'S SOCCER: Junior captain Claire Kostelnik shared this week's Capital Athletic Conference Offensive Player of the Week award. 
MCDANIEL VOLLEYBALL: McDaniel won all three sets by double digits, defeating Ursinus 3-0. Madeline Rose led the Green Terror (12-5, 3-1 CC) with eight kills and three total blocks. Karla Thiele paced the Bears (5-13, 0-5 CC) with seven kills and six digs. 
FROSTBURG FIELD HOCKEY: The Bobcats dropped a 5-1 decision to No. 10 Lynchburg College, Monday evening. 
BOWIE STATE VOLLEYBALL: The Bulldogs dropped their second straight match on Monday night, falling 3-0 to the Lady Panthers of Virginia Union University. The Lady Bulldogs dip to 5-14 overall, 2-6 in the CIAA and 0-5 within the division. Virginia Union snapped a two match slide and pull their season mark even at 7-7 and improve to 5-2 in conference play and 3-1 in the CIAA North.
